00:53:35,480 --> 00:53:44,681
So, Yvonne is really interested in the punishments that people get, and of course, interested in the punishments that the children get.

669
00:53:44,681 --> 00:53:45,880
So, now what?

670
00:53:46,440 --> 00:53:56,921
We're almost there, because it now turns out that the way the book works, it shows you that you aren't in the position to give back the ticket.

671
00:53:56,920 --> 00:54:14,840
Yvonne, the sadist, who is relishing the torturing of these children, can't be giving back the ticket to the world saying, I don't want to be in a world in which people torture children, because he's totally hooked on the world in which people torture children.

672
00:54:15,721 --> 00:54:44,601
So, now the conclusion is his whole argument is wrong, because it looks like his relation to the world is like to a fraternity or a movie or a play, but not because they're just local and there's more to the world, but because he thinks you can just leave the world, the way you can leave the fraternity or the play where you're not responsible for what is vulgar and sadistic and stupid and prejudiced that might be going on there.

673
00:54:44,920 --> 00:54:50,281
It's clear that he is doing just the kind of thing that he wants to condemn.

674
00:54:51,081 --> 00:55:00,160
So, he can't, as the righteous person, leave the world condemning the suffering of the children when he really enjoys the suffering of children.

675
00:54:59,241 --> 00:55:03,040
That's Dostoevsky's argument.

676
00:55:03,360 --> 00:55:20,880
So now, I can't tell you much more about this because it's a plot thing, but I'll tell you a little: that Yvonne gets more and more general, and it turns out that being an eyewitness is a very dangerous thing to be.

677
00:55:21,201 --> 00:55:28,481
And it turns out that Yvonne takes responsibility for much of the evil in the book, finally.

678
00:55:28,480 --> 00:55:33,040
And it turns out, too, that I was reading the notes for the brothers Karamatsov.

